e trade. People often used cannabis to cope with oppressive working conditions under colonialism, as a recreational drug, and in religious and political movements. This expansive look at Africa's importance to the development of human knowledge about marijuana will challenge everything readers thought they knew about one of the world's most ubiquitous plants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCannabisxEconomic aspectszAfricaxHistory. 0aCannabisxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aCannabiszAfricaxHistory. 0aMarijuanaxEconomic aspectszAfricaxHistory. 0aMarijuanaxSocial aspectszAfricaxHistory. 0aMarijuanaxTherapeutic usezAfricaxHistory. 0aMarijuanazAfricaxHistory. 0aMedicinal plantszAfricaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478004530zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478004530423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478004530.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles